{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"eb4434f9-0019-485d-a048-5d714a561bdc","content":"Since you're using MSTest 3.8.0 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, hang detection is built in. Just run:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --hang-dump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nThis will abort and produce a hang dump if any test doesn't complete within 5 minutes. You can also add `--hang-dump-path ./dumps` to control where the dump files are saved.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8cafb4af-636f-4173-b87a-c8fa8796efa1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is using MSTest with Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner (configured in global.json). To add a 5-minute hang timeout, I can use the `--hangdump-timeout` option when running tests, or configure it in the project/runsettings.\n\nSince they're using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (the new test runner), the hang dump feature is available via the `Microsoft.Testing.Platform.Extensions.HangDump` package or built-in options.\n\nFor MSTest 3.8.0 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, I can:\n\n1. Add `--hang-dump-timeout 5m` to the `dotnet test` command line\n\n\n2. Or configure it via a `.runsettings` file\n\nThe simplest approach is running `dotnet test --hang-dump-timeout 5m`, though I should verify whether the hang dump extension comes bundled with MSTest 3.8.0 or if they need to add the package separately.\n\nLooking at the MSTest 3.8.0 dependencies, the hang dump extension should be included transitively through the testing platform, so the command alone should work to dump and abort any test hanging beyond 5 minutes.","outputTokens":526},"id":"0266f3ed-b673-4589-9359-a8f7d9b27e9f","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:59:30.517Z","parentId":"e36cbfca-4832-41f3-bef9-1529b4b2e9bb"}
